006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs- William Snelling had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with William Snelling."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1425–1509":"1425–1509","1450–1529":"1450–1529","1488–Female":"1488–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1425":"1425","1488":"1488","1450":"1450","1509":"1509","1529":"1529","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1425–1509":"1425–1509","1450–1529":"1450–1529","1488–Female":"1488–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1425":"1425","1488":"1488","1450":"1450","1509":"1509","1529":"1529","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1425–1509":"1425–1509","1450–1529":"1450–1529","1488–Female":"1488–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1425":"1425","1488":"1488","1450":"1450","1509":"1509","1529":"1529","England":"Angleterre","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs- William Snelling a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille avec William Snelling."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1425–1509":"1425–1509","1450–1529":"1450–1529","1488–Female":"1488–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1425":"1425","1488":"1488","1450":"1450","1509":"1509","1529":"1529","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs- William Snelling hatte mit William Snelling mindestens 1 Sohn und 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"–":"Desede","1425–1509":"1425–1509","1450–1529":"1450–1529","1488–Female":"